What is the distribution of X-bar (X1, X2, X3 ~ iid UNIF(0,1))

N <- 10^5
n <- 3

simmeans <- numeric(N)

for(i in 1:N){
  simsample <- runif(n, 0, 1)
  simmeans[i] <- mean(simsample)
}

hist(simmeans)

mean(simmeans)
## [1] 0.499788
var(simmeans)
## [1] 0.02772317
qqPlot(simmeans)

## [1] 84328 59841

The shape is not normal here so we cannot use CLT or Pnorm

So,

mean(simmeans >= 0.7)
## [1] 0.12088

What if I tried to use pnorm incorrectly?

pnorm(.7,.5, sqrt(1/36), F)
## [1] 0.1150697

What is the distribution of X-bar (X1, X2, X3 ~ iid EXP(0,1))

Bootstraping fish examples

FISH <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/STAT-JET-ASU/Datasets/master/Chihara/Walleye.csv")

str(FISH)
## 'data.frame':    60 obs. of  2 variables:
##  $ Length: num  11.1 16.1 20.7 14.3 11.5 15.7 12.5 15.3 26.6 17.8 ...
##  $ Weight: num  0.4 1.39 2.8 1.03 0.5 0.9 0.6 1.3 7.5 2.2 ...
summary(FISH)
##      Length          Weight      
##  Min.   : 9.10   Min.   : 0.300  
##  1st Qu.:12.78   1st Qu.: 0.775  
##  Median :15.85   Median : 1.250  
##  Mean   :16.52   Mean   : 1.989  
##  3rd Qu.:20.35   3rd Qu.: 2.800  
##  Max.   :29.30   Max.   :10.300
boxplot(FISH$Length)

inchesmean <- mean(FISH$Length)
inchesstdv <- sd(FISH$Length)
inches_n   <- length(FISH$Length)
inches_df  <- inches_n - 1

# what if we do a traditional 95% CI?

  CI_LB <- inchesmean - qt(0.975, inches_df) * inchesstdv / sqrt(inches_n)
  CI_UB <- inchesmean + qt(0.975, inches_df) * inchesstdv / sqrt(inches_n)
  print(c(CI_LB, CI_UB))
## [1] 15.29939 17.74394
# bootstrap 95% percentile interval
  
N <- 10^4
bootmeans <- numeric(N)
for (i in 1:N){
  bootsample   <- sample(FISH$Length, inches_n, replace = TRUE)
  bootmeans[i] <- mean(bootsample)
}

quantile(bootmeans, c(0.025, 0.975))
##     2.5%    97.5% 
## 15.35833 17.74004
# is the distribution approximately normal?
hist(bootmeans)

require(car)
qqPlot(bootmeans)

## [1] 4845 2881

Same thing but with weight

boxplot(FISH$Weight)

weightmean <- mean(FISH$Weight)
weightstdv <- sd(FISH$Weight)
weight_n   <- length(FISH$Weight)
weight_df  <- weight_n - 1

# traditional 95% CI

CI_LB <- weightmean - qt(0.975, weight_df) * weightstdv / sqrt(weight_n)
CI_UB <- weightmean + qt(0.975, weight_df) * weightstdv / sqrt(weight_n)
print(c(CI_LB, CI_UB))
## [1] 1.488625 2.488708
# bootstrap 95% percentile interval

N <- 10^4
bootmeans <- numeric(N)
for (i in 1:N){
  bootsample   <- sample(FISH$Weight, weight_n, replace = TRUE)
  bootmeans[i] <- mean(bootsample)
}

quantile(bootmeans, c(0.025, 0.975))
##     2.5%    97.5% 
## 1.535829 2.509333
# is the distribution approximately normal?
hist(bootmeans)

require(car)
qqPlot(bootmeans)

## [1] 7893 4876
